Scenario
You have been hired as a lead architect at NovaPay, a fintech company building a white-label corporate payments platform for mid-to-large UK and US banks. The platform will be used by corporate clients of those banks — companies like retailers, manufacturers, and financial institutions who need to make domestic and international payments on behalf of their business.
The engineering team is starting from scratch and you have been asked to design the core payments module in Java before the first sprint begins.

Business Context
NovaPay’s banking clients onboard their own corporate customers onto the platform. Each corporate customer has multiple users — a finance manager, a treasury officer, a payments clerk — each of whom should only be able to see and do exactly what their role permits. A payments clerk at Company A should never be able to see Company B’s transactions, initiate a payment from an account they are not entitled to, or approve a payment they themselves created.
Payments can be initiated in two ways. A user can log into the web application and fill in a payment form, or they can upload a file containing hundreds or thousands of payment instructions in bulk. Both channels must be supported simultaneously.
Once a payment is initiated, it cannot go straight to the bank’s underlying payment processor. Every payment must pass through a review and approval process — at least one person other than the person who created the payment must review and approve it before it can be sent. For higher-value or higher-risk payments the rules are stricter, requiring multiple approvers. These rules vary by payment scheme and amount.
The platform must support the following payment schemes out of the box.
For UK payments: Faster Payments (FPS) for near-instant low-value transfers, CHAPS for same-day high-value sterling transfers, and BACS for three-day bulk payroll and supplier payments.
For US payments: ACH for batch electronic transfers and Fedwire for real-time high-value transfers. International payments will use SWIFT.
All payments, regardless of how they were initiated or which scheme they use, must be converted into ISO 20022 pain.001 format before being sent to the bank’s downstream payment processor, which is a third-party system called GPP. NovaPay has no control over GPP and must treat it as an external black box.

Key Requirements
Entitlements. Each user’s permissions are defined across multiple dimensions simultaneously. A user may be entitled to initiate payments only from specific accounts, only for specific legal entities within their corporate group, only up to a certain monetary amount, only on certain payment schemes, only through the UI or only via file upload, or only using pre-approved payment templates. The entitlement model must be flexible enough to combine all of these constraints together.
Maker-Checker Workflow. Every payment must follow a workflow where the creator (maker) submits the payment and one or more other authorised users (checkers) must approve it. The number of approvers required is determined dynamically based on the payment scheme and the payment amount. As examples: an FPS payment under £10,000 may require one checker; a CHAPS payment over £50,000 may require two independent checkers; a SWIFT payment may always require dual control regardless of amount. A checker must not be the same person as the maker. A checker must also be entitled to approve payments on the relevant account and scheme.
Execution Modes. The platform must support three modes of payment execution. Real-time payments are submitted to GPP immediately upon approval and a status is returned synchronously. Async payments are used when a file contains multiple beneficiaries — these are queued and processed in the background without the user waiting. Future-dated payments are scheduled by the user for a specific value date up to 90 days in the future and must be held securely until that date arrives, then submitted automatically.
File Payments. Two types of file upload are supported. The first is a single bulk file in a scheme-specific format such as NACHA for ACH or BACS Standard 18 — this is treated as one file-level payment instruction. The second is a file containing a group of individual payment instructions, each of which is extracted, validated, and processed independently but linked back to the originating file for reporting purposes.
Transaction Visibility. Users must be able to view all transactions they are entitled to see, whether those transactions were created through the UI or via file upload. The view must respect entitlement boundaries — a user should only see transactions on accounts and schemes they are permitted to access.
Export. Users can export their entitled transaction data. If the result set contains fewer than 5,000 records the export must be delivered immediately as a direct download. If the result set exceeds 5,000 records the system must process the export asynchronously in the background, store the output file, and notify the user when it is ready to download.
Reliability. No payment instruction should be lost due to a service crash, network failure, or infrastructure issue at any point in its lifecycle — from the moment the user submits it to the moment GPP acknowledges it.
